Welcome to the=C2=A02,449=C2=A0newly Not Boring people=C2=A0who have joined=
 us since last Monday! If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=A0167,924=
 smart, curious folks by subscribing here:=20
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Monday! What a year the past week has been.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m not going to write a piece on FTX today, other than to touch on=
 it briefly, not because I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s an important st=
ory, but because it=E2=80=99s been written about millions of times over the=
 past week and I don=E2=80=99t have much new to add.=C2=A0
FTX US sponsored Not Boring Founders and a couple of newsletter editions. I=
 would never and will never work with a sponsor whose products I wouldn=E2=
=80=99t use myself. I just got FTX wrong. I was so comfortable with FTX tha=
t when they asked to deposit my payment in my FTX US account instead of my =
bank account, I said yes without a second thought. I never imagined they=E2=
=80=99d become insolvent, and traded/kept funds in that account for months =
without a worry. I only avoided getting wiped out because I got lucky: I wa=
nted to stake the ETH and MATIC I bought there, so I moved everything on-ch=
ain a couple of weeks ago. The story is ongoing, but it looks like FTX and =
SBF committed fraud, deceit, theft, and misuse of customer funds, and I hop=
e that they=E2=80=99re held accountable, and that customer funds can be res=
tored, to the fullest extent possible.
Mario Gabriele comes closest to my thoughts and feelings on the whole thing=
 in his beautifully written The Casino and the Genie [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/c90b179d-6912-4558-8121-5f807ce33a10?r=3D9p0gt ]. I=E2=80=99m wor=
king on a bigger piece that in part explains why I think crypto is still va=
luable and inevitable for next week.=C2=A0
Indirectly, though, this piece is about FTX, or the impact of its actions o=
n belief. While it=E2=80=99s hard to measure precisely, belief is one of th=
e most important inputs to tech and crypto valuations, even though it doesn=
=E2=80=99t show up in a DCF model.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Discounting Belief
Companies are valued based on the present value of future cash flows. Inves=
tors guess how much money companies will generate in the future, and then a=
pply some basic math to figure out what all of that money is worth today.=
=C2=A0
As rates have risen, there=E2=80=99s been a lot of talk about the negative =
impact of higher interest rates on asset prices. There=E2=80=99s been talk =
about how higher rates and an impending recession will impact future earnin=
gs. There=E2=80=99s been less talk about what the current environment has d=
one to belief, and about the impact of belief on asset prices.=C2=A0
Particularly for the more speculative, future-looking companies that we tal=
k about in Not Boring, prices are a function of the discount rate of future=
 cash flows and investors=E2=80=99 belief that those future cash flows will=
 ever materialize. We=E2=80=99ll call that the Belief Rate.
Discount rates and Belief Rates are inversely related: higher interest rate=
s, lower belief in the future. As far as I know, there=E2=80=99s no formula=
 that ties the two, but you can feel it in the sentiment shift ever since t=
he Fed started raising rates. Things that looked promising then look stupid=
 now. Big dreams were as good as gold then; they look like fool=E2=80=99s g=
old now. The truth is usually somewhere in between.=C2=A0
The Belief Rate isn=E2=80=99t a real thing. In spreadsheets, belief manifes=
ts in lower cash flow estimates or higher discount rates. But when you sepa=
rate the discount rate and the Belief Rate, things start to make more sense=
, and a more clear path emerges for both investors and entrepreneurs. So we=
=E2=80=99ll address each separately, and then discuss what to do in a low-b=
elief environment. Let=E2=80=99s start with the basics: the discount rate.=
=C2=A0
The Discount Rate
Despite a brief, CPI-driven respite last week, 2022 has been a brutal year.=
 Growth stocks are down bad, crypto is down bad, and startup valuations are=
 down bad, whether or not that=E2=80=99s reflected in investors=E2=80=99 ma=
rks yet. Turns out, a lot of the hope that people felt in 2020 and 2021 abo=
ut these companies=E2=80=99 future prospects was really just the ultra-low =
discount rates talking.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CDiscount rate=E2=80=9D is a financial term for the rate that inves=
tors expect to receive from an investment, or the company=E2=80=99s cost to=
 borrow money. Practically, it=E2=80=99s used in net present value (NPV) ca=
lculations to calculate what a future cash flow is worth today.=C2=A0
The formula says, =E2=80=9CTake the expected cash flow in some future year =
(R) and divide it by 1 + the discount rate raised to however many years in =
the future it is.=E2=80=9D The NPV is essentially compounding in reverse. S=
o if you expect to make a million dollars in ten years, the discount rate h=
elps investors figure out what they=E2=80=99d be willing to buy those milli=
on dollars for today.=C2=A0
For the first half of this piece, let=E2=80=99s hold that expected future c=
ash flow constant and look at what happens when you change the discount rat=
e. A toy model helps explain its impact.=C2=A0
At a 0% discount rate, your $1 million future cash flow is worth exactly as=
 much to you today as it would be ten or twenty years in the future: $1 mil=
lion. If a company promises, =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re going to make $1 millio=
n dollars in 2042,=E2=80=9D you might say, =E2=80=9CCool, I will pay you $1=
 million right now if you give me that $1 million when you make it in 2042.=
=E2=80=9D To be fair, you don=E2=80=99t have much of a choice. You need to =
put your money somewhere when keeping it in cash yields 0%.
At a 5% discount rate, though, your $1 million future cash flow is worth le=
ss today. If it=E2=80=99s ten years in the future, it=E2=80=99s worth $613,=
913 today. If it=E2=80=99s twenty years in the future, it=E2=80=99s worth $=
376,889 today. The higher the discount rate goes, and the further out the c=
ash flow, the more measly that cash flow looks today. At 20%, $1 million tw=
enty years from now is worth only $26,084 today.
The logic goes something like this: if I can get 20% on a US Treasury Bond,=
 and I invest $26,084 in that US Treasury Bond today, it will be worth $1 m=
illion in twenty years. That money is as guaranteed as any money in the wor=
ld. So I=E2=80=99m not willing to buy your $1 million for any more than $26=
,084 today when I have a safer way to get $1 million in 2042 for the same a=
mount.=C2=A0
Actually, that=E2=80=99s as rosy a scenario for the company as possible. If=
 you can get 20% on US Treasuries, the =E2=80=9Crisk-free rate,=E2=80=9D th=
en the actual discount rate for the company will be higher, because it cost=
s companies more to borrow than it costs the US Government. The difference =
is=C2=A0 called the risk premium.
Let=E2=80=99s say that your company=E2=80=99s risk premium is 5% and 10-yea=
r US Treasuries are paying 20% (a crazy number, but we came close in the ea=
rly 1980s). That means that your discount rate is 25%, and your $1 million =
in 2042 dollars is only worth $11,529 today.
Still with me? Why was that important?=C2=A0
Companies are theoretically valued based on the sum of their discounted cas=
h flows. If the company expects to generate $1 million in cash flow every y=
ear for the next twenty years, then the company is worth $20 million today =
at a 0% discount rate, or $3,953,883 at a 25% discount rate. The same exact=
