xcept for the discount rate.=C2=A0
Those are oversimplified numbers for illustrative purposes. They=E2=80=99re=
 extreme, too. But the extremes help paint a picture of what=E2=80=99s goin=
g on in the markets right now.=C2=A0
The obvious piece of what=E2=80=99s going on in the markets is that the Fed=
 is aggressively hiking rates. From a low of 0.52% (or 52 bps in finance-sp=
eak) in August 2020, the 10 Year US Treasury yield has increased to 4.14%.=
=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s only like 3.5%. How much could it hurt valuations?=C2=A0
Using the 10 Year UST as the discount rate, $1 million in ten years was wor=
th $949,457 in August 2020 and is only worth $666,537 today, a 30% decline =
based on nothing changing except the 10 Year UST yield!=C2=A0
This is also why stocks and crypto skyrocketed on Thursday when Consumer Pr=
ice Index (CPI) growth, which measures inflation, came in lower than expect=
ed. People expect that lower CPI growth will mean the Fed will stop raising=
