s projected earnings, and the relative impact of rising rates on each.=C2=
=A0
There=E2=80=99s some noise in there. For example, there=E2=80=99s a war goi=
ng on, which is presumably good for defense stocks, and tech companies=E2=
=80=99 corporate and consumer customers are more sensitive to a recession t=
han the DoD is. A more clear picture emerges when you look at the response =
to Thursday=E2=80=99s CPI print:
The shapes of each index=E2=80=99s charts are nearly identical, but they=E2=
=80=99re moving on different scales, with the riskiest and growthiest Nasda=
q Composite Index increasing twice as much as the more conservative, slower=
-growing Dow Jones Industrial Average. The discount rate impacts growth sto=
cks more than others, in both directions, because their cash flows are furt=
her in the future.
ETH, and crypto more broadly, is even more sensitive to discount rates than=
 the Nasdaq because its future value is so far out and speculative. Startup=
s don=E2=80=99t trade in real-time, but if they did, they=E2=80=99d probabl=
y move somewhere in between the Nasdaq and ETH, because their future cash f=
lows are further in the future than the average public tech company but mos=
t do have the ability to produce spreadsheets with numbers that can be used=
 to run a traditional valuation model, even if it=E2=80=99s a very uncertai=
n one.=C2=A0
Crypto, startups, and tech stocks are also more sensitive to a more fickle =
input: belief.
Everything we=E2=80=99ve talked about so far is just the math part, and far=
 smarter people than me have weighed in on the impact of rising interest ra=
tes on valuations with more nuance. This Invest Like the Best episode on ma=
cro with Bob Elliott (which I promise I listened to after writing everythin=
g above) is a good listen on that front:
The other part of it is hand-wavier, more vibes-based. Let=E2=80=99s call i=
t the Belief Rate.
The Belief Rate
So far, we=E2=80=99ve held the expected future cash flow constant and playe=
d with the discount rate. But holding that expected future cash flow consta=
nt is a big assumption, especially for technology and crypto companies whos=
e histories are shorter and whose promised best days are far in the future.=
 For the second half of the piece, we=E2=80=99ll focus on the expected futu=
re cash flows.=C2=A0
The Belief Rate is something like a conversion rate between a company=E2=80=
=99s projections and the future cash flow number that shows up in investors=
=E2=80=99 models.=C2=A0
In practice, companies don=E2=80=99t provide guidance far into the future. =
It=E2=80=99s up to analysts to take everything the company has done in the =
past and said about the future and build models that turn all of that into =
numbers. And those analysts=E2=80=99 cash flow projections come with their =
own belief on the company=E2=80=99s future prospects baked in. No one is bu=
ilding models that calculate Rt*b, they=E2=80=99re just putting in an Rt fo=
r each future cash flow that implicitly accounts for their own belief and a=
nalysis. If anything, they=E2=80=99re backing into something similar by adj=
usting the risk premium reflected in the discount rate. But I think it=E2=
=80=99s worth breaking out the Belief Rate as a separate thing to understan=
d what happens when belief, in the market, an industry, or a specific asset=
, changes.
(Interestingly, in a 2012 report [ https://substack.com/redirect/ea577b0e-0=
a99-4988-a0d4-df59da2883bf?r=3D9p0gt ], McKinsey said that project analysts=
 too often increase the risk premium in their discount rate due to uncertai=
nty about their cash flow projections, and recommends that they should inst=
ead keep the discount rate at the actual cost of capital and use a weighted=
 average multiple cash flow projections instead=E2=80=A6 kind of like an in=
ternal Belief Rate.)
The Belief Rate is connected to the discount rate =E2=80=93 when rates are =
low, people have to put their cash somewhere, and they want to believe =E2=
=80=93 but it=E2=80=99s also tied to more nebulous general sentiment. That =
piece is harder to describe, but if you=E2=80=99ve spent time on tech Twitt=
er, crypto Twitter, or fintwit, or just read tech press, over the past coup=
le of years, you=E2=80=99ve felt it. The souring market =E2=80=93 plus a wa=
r, crypto blowups, politics, and a general hangover from the past few years=
 of excess =E2=80=93 precipitated a Vibe Shift. The Vibe Shift hit the Beli=
ef Rate hard.=C2=A0
Just as Treasury yields impact every company=E2=80=99s discount rate, the V=
ibe hits every company=E2=80=99s Belief Rate. In a bear market, belief in e=
verything suffers. And just as the discount rates hit companies with a high=
er percentage of their cash flows further in the future harder, the Belief =
Rate hits companies making bigger, more speculative future-looking bets har=
der, too.=C2=A0
For the past few years, while rates were low and growth was king, the Belie=
f Rate for bold tech companies was close to 100%. If a company said they we=
re going to build AI-Operated Space Zoos and planned to generate $100 milli=
on of cash flow by 2028, investors responded, =E2=80=9COnly $100 million? Y=
=E2=80=99know, a lot of people undershot Uber=E2=80=99s TAM. Let=E2=80=99s =
say $200 million, and here=E2=80=99s $50 million to help you get there fast=
er.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Everyone, me included, was a little drunk on a cocktail of cheap money and =
easy demand.
Rising interest rates and a (looming?) recession closed the open bar. Inves=
tors are sobering up. And when they look at that =E2=80=9C$1 million of cas=
h flows in ten years=E2=80=9D projection, all of a sudden, they=E2=80=99re =
going:=C2=A0
The degree to which investors don=E2=80=99t believe you depends on a bunch =
of things, like how good a job you=E2=80=99ve done doing what you said you =
were going to do, how crazy the assumptions baked into your projections are=
, and how far in the future your projected cash flow is.=C2=A0
If Lockheed Martin says they=E2=80=99re going to generate $6.5 billion in F=
ree Cash Flow next year, you can take that to the bank (plus or minus a few=
