=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">At a 0% discount rate, your $1 million future cash flow is worth exactly =
as much to you today as it would be ten or twenty years in the future: $1 m=
illion. If a company promises, &#8220;We&#8217;re going to make $1 million =
dollars in 2042,&#8221; you might say, &#8220;Cool, I will pay you $1 milli=
on right now if you give me that $1 million when you make it in 2042.&#8221=
; To be fair, you don&#8217;t have much of a choice. You need to put your m=
oney somewhere when keeping it in cash yields 0%.</p><p style=3D"color: #40=
4040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>At a 5=
% discount rate, though, your $1 million future cash flow is worth less tod=
ay. If it&#8217;s ten years in the future, it&#8217;s worth $613,913 today.=
 If it&#8217;s twenty years in the future, it&#8217;s worth $376,889 today.=
 The higher the discount rate goes, and the further out the cash flow, the =
more measly that cash flow looks today. </span><strong>At 20%, $1 million t=
wenty years from now is worth only $26,084 today</strong><span>.</span></p>=
<p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">The logic goes something like this: if I can get 20% on a US Trea=
sury Bond, and I invest $26,084 in that US Treasury Bond today, it will be =
worth $1 million in twenty years. That money is as guaranteed as any money =
in the world. So I&#8217;m not willing to buy your $1 million for any more =
than $26,084 today when I have a safer way to get $1 million in 2042 for th=
e same amount.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Actually, that&#8217;s as rosy a sc=
enario for the company as possible. If you can get 20% on US Treasuries, th=
e &#8220;risk-free rate,&#8221; then the actual discount rate for the compa=
ny will be higher, because it costs companies more to borrow than it costs =
the US Government. The difference is&#160; called the </span><strong>risk p=
remium</strong><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Let&#8217;s say that your =
company&#8217;s risk premium is 5% and 10-year US Treasuries are paying 20%=
 (a crazy number, but we came close in the early 1980s). That means that yo=
ur discount rate is 25%, and </span><strong>your $1 million in 2042 dollars=
 is only worth $11,529 today</strong><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #=
404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Still with=
 me? Why was that important?&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size=
: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Companies are theoret=
ically valued based on the </span><strong>sum of their discounted cash flow=
s</strong><span>. If the company expects to generate $1 million in cash flo=
w every year for the next twenty years, then the company is worth $20 milli=
on today at a 0% discount rate, or $3,953,883 at a 25% discount rate. </spa=
n><strong>The same exact business is worth one-fifth as much today if you c=
hange nothing about it except for the discount rate.&#160;</strong></p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;">Those are oversimplified numbers for illustrative purposes. They&#821=
7;re extreme, too. But the extremes help paint a picture of what&#8217;s go=
ing on in the markets right now.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The obvious piece of wh=
at&#8217;s going on in the markets is that the Fed is aggressively hiking r=
ates. From a low of 0.52% (or 52 bps in finance-speak) in August 2020, the =
10 Year US Treasury yield has increased to 4.14%.&#160;</p><div class=3D"ca=
