ure></div><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;">The Belief Rate is something like a conversion rate bet=
ween a company&#8217;s projections and the future cash flow number that sho=
ws up in investors&#8217; models.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In practice, companies=
 don&#8217;t provide guidance far into the future. It&#8217;s up to analyst=
s to take everything the company has done in the past and said about the fu=
ture and build models that turn all of that into numbers. And those analyst=
s&#8217; cash flow projections come with their own belief on the company&#8=
217;s future prospects baked in. No one is building models that calculate R=
t*b, they&#8217;re just putting in an Rt for each future cash flow that imp=
licitly accounts for their own belief and analysis. If anything, they&#8217=
;re backing into something similar by adjusting the risk premium reflected =
in the discount rate. But I think it&#8217;s worth breaking out the Belief =
Rate as a separate thing to understand what happens when belief, in the mar=
ket, an industry, or a specific asset, changes.</p><p style=3D"color: #4040=
40; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>(Interes=
tingly, in a </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/ea577b0e-0a99-=
4988-a0d4-df59da2883bf?r=3D9p0gt" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-de=
coration: underline;">2012 report</a><span>, McKinsey said that project ana=
lysts too often increase the risk premium in their discount rate due to unc=
ertainty about their cash flow projections, and recommends that they should=
 instead keep the discount rate at the actual cost of capital and use a wei=
ghted average multiple cash flow projections instead&#8230; kind of like an=
 internal Belief Rate.)</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The Belief Rate is connec=
ted to the discount rate &#8211; when rates are low, people have to put the=
ir cash somewhere, and they </span><em>want </em><span>to believe &#8211; b=
ut it&#8217;s also tied to more nebulous general sentiment. That piece is h=
arder to describe, but if you&#8217;ve spent time on tech Twitter, crypto T=
witter, or fintwit, or just read tech press, over the past couple of years,=
 you&#8217;ve felt it. The souring market &#8211; plus a war, crypto blowup=
s, politics, and a general hangover from the past few years of excess &#821=
1; precipitated a </span><strong>Vibe Shift</strong><span>. The Vibe Shift =
hit the Belief Rate hard.&#160;</span></p><div class=3D"captioned-image-con=
